1
00:00:00,005 --> 00:00:09,485
When creating demos, switching between
terminal and browser used to lose all your
terminal state. Let me show you how
persistent sessions fix this.

2
00:00:20,242 --> 00:00:22,714
Now switching to browser.

3
00:00:25,565 --> 00:00:30,461
Back to terminal. Watch - the state is
preserved.

4
00:00:36,907 --> 00:00:40,723
Directory and environment variables are
intact!

5
00:00:40,729 --> 00:00:45,721
Now for named sessions - running server
and client terminals simultaneously.

6
00:00:55,584 --> 00:00:58,896
Server running on port twelve thousand
one.

7
00:00:59,202 --> 00:01:01,890
In a separate client terminal:

8
00:01:05,853 --> 00:01:08,469
Client fetches from server.

9
00:01:08,803 --> 00:01:11,731
Switching back to the server session.

10
00:01:15,083 --> 00:01:18,611
And our original terminal still has its
state.

11
00:01:26,865 --> 00:01:31,713
That's persistent sessions and named
sessions - complex demos made simple.

